,Recommended,220740,27751145,"Posted: 26 November, 2016",all,streat0r,"After playing the first instalment of Deponia, I had quite a few criticisms, mostly about the characters and storyline. However, despite these flaws, I did enjoy the game and so I couldn't resist continuing on to the next chapter. I much preferred the puzzles in this chapter, although I'm not sure if it's because I was now used to the way the game ""thinks"" and thus found it easier.I liked many of the game mechanics and was able to play most of the game without any walkthrough. Again, however, some of the puzzles were quite obscure, or just out of reach so that when I did look up the solution, I either thought ""What? How was I supposed to figure that out?"" or ""Argh, I basically did that!"". Still, I appreciated a lot of the scenes and in particular the different places to explore.The humour is still great, and some of the new characters added some depth to familiar scenarios. As with the first instalment, I still think there was too much dialogue in some places. I also still have major issues with the representation of the female characters in this game, in particular the way Goal is objectified not just by Rufus's creepy possessive pursuit of her as a prize or trophy, but also in the game mechanics. There are also a couple of cutscenes that were just unnecessarily vulgar and borderline predatory. Goal is a great character, and I love the additional dynamism her character got in this chapter, which made it even more of a shame to see her remain as an object to be ogled and played with. Blech.Overall, it's still a good game, though I wouldn't pay full price for it. I got both Deponia and Chaos on Deponia in the sale and I'm very happy about that. I wouldn't pay more than €10/$10 for either chapter. If you can get the whole lot on sale, even better."
,Recommended,220740,33975747,Posted: 2 August,all,Zipomatic,"NOTE: Ignore the playtime given on this game, I actually played this as part of the ""Complete Journey"" package and put around 14 hours or so into the game.How much enjoyment you will gain from ""Chaos"" once again depends of how much you like or dislike the main character Rufus. Yes he is still annoying, but I don't think he is quite as bad as he was in the original Deponia. Gameplay wise, things are pretty much the same as the original, but there have been a few added twists here and there that make things more fun.The main wrinkle to things this time around is that Goal has three personalities now, and you can choose between each one, so if one of them refuses to do something, another may might react completely differently. Most of the puzzles are not too outrageous (a couple however are very “out of the box”) but there are occasions where you are doing the correct thing, just not at the right time, so you assume that is not the solution to the problem and move on (except it IS the solution)  Really, for most of the time you have a feeling that you know what you need to do, it's just figuring out how to actually DO it is the annoying part.Better than the original in every way, if you want to keep up with Rufus and company, give this a go. If you hated things about the original Deponia, this installment will not change your mind."
