76561197980429671,Not Recommended,220740,20708498,"Posted: 23 January, 2016",all,Bubba Jones,"The second of a three part series where Daedalic takes on Monkey Island and should be looked at as part of the series.  This is the weakest episode in the series.  If you played and enjoyed the first game, you will enjoy this one.  If not, you can stop here and not bother continuing.  If you are starting the series fresh you should pick up the first one.As a part of Daedalic's Monkey Island-like humor series, the jokes are in there, and they are numerous.  Again, I can't say anything here is any better than the other two games.  Translation problems factor in and some of the humor will leave you confused, as it did in the other two games.  Some of the humor is unintentional because of the aforesaid translation.  Some of them, a few of the less funny sexist jokes, the Scandinavian guy, that part where you ----- -- baby dolphins ---- ----, did not leave me insulted so much as wondering how the writers could have believed I would think that funny.  Perhaps this is just me not entirely getting the German sense of humor or me just calling out tasteless as I see it.The pace of the story has slowed down a lot.  A large chunk of the game involves character development for Goal.  Rufus changes little from the first game and any hopes  you may have that he is really a decent person are taken outside and shot several times.  Any character development he receives follows the direction of writer's butt monkey and someone the player wishes something bad would happen to.  Fortunately, you do become attached to the colorful cast of side characters and part of the enjoyment of playing the game involves seeing who's life Rufus will ruin next.The gameplay shows Daedalic's polish to the adventure gaming genre which leave you wondering why nobody else tried some of the changes they made.  As an example, the inventory can be brought up and down with a hotkey on your mouse wheel.  Details are well drawn and animated, with your attention going to things you should pay attention to so you don't have to do the mouse search across a background for that one object.  There are keyboard shortcuts and a highlight button to show all the intractable objects.  Things like this keep me playing Daedalic's games even through parts I don't enjoy.The puzzles are more complicated than they were in the first game.  If you don't like being in an area with a large bloated zone with several puzzles dropped in your lap at the same time, working on all of them at the same time, that is the entire first - and largest - part of the game.  Nothing drove me to frustration and any problems could be solved by thinking about them for a while, but there is a large area to cover and a lot of things to tinker with in order to figure out what you need to do.There are a few stand out moments, the first puzzle you solve, teaching you how to apply several gameplay basics, after you go through the basic tutorial was hilarious.  Hilarious enough for me to restart and replay it a few times.  The second moment was when I had to go and change the game's options to solve a puzzle.Your mileage may vary for a lot of this game but I'd still call it the weakest episode in the series where Daedalic tries to correct some of the problems made in Deponia and end up creating new mistakes.  If you are not into Daedalic's adventure games or adventure gaming in general this is one you can skip.  If you are into the Deponia series and really enjoyed the first game enough to continue the story then, by all means, pick this one up."
